<dl id="n03145d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03145d">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03145d"> 145(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> present of foes&apos; tongue <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03145d"><li>FW 248.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/lexkf.htm#n03145d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/l39kf.htm#n03145d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03145d">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="kfBd3" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kfBd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kf/kfd3.htm#n03145d">Draft: II.1&sect;6B.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Nightingale&apos;s Song, 146]</font>: In one hand <font color="green">[Tristram]</font> still carried his bow and two arrows, in the other two long locks of hair. &hellip; &ldquo;Seest thou these fine tresses? They are Denoalen&apos;s. I have avenged thee on him. <small> Joseph B&eacute;dier, <a name="JBLR1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JBLR1"><cite title="source">Le roman de Tristan et Iseut</cite></a> (1900) XIII &lsquo;La Voix du Rossignol [Italian <i>Usignolo</i>]&rsquo;, 147</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Entered by <a name="sh1017a" href="sh1all.htm#sh1017a">Sheet i-17(a)</a>. Joyce seems to conflate this with the tale of Tristan&apos;s slaying of the Irish dragon. The knight cuts the dragon&apos;s tongue out and puts it into his hose, but its venom causes him to faint. The king&apos;s seneschal, who wants Iseult [the Fair] (the prize for the dragon-slayer) for himself, then falsely claims victory. Iseult then finds Tristan and the dragon&apos;s tongue, the proof of the death of the dragon. </mm> </dd></dl>
